Paul Qureshi wrote:

>Really? I guess that is why you are trying to ensure an open ended
>future for the Warp3D API... but they must have got seriously off track
>if they had to start over with an incompatable API.
>
Well, the next generation of Warp3D will most likely have an 
incompatible API with a compatibility wrapper thrown in. There are some 
things in Warp3D that do not translate too well to T&L hardware, so 
there needs to be some basic changes...

Yes, DX8 is more or less incompatible (rather more than less :-) with 
its predecessors, but all for the better IMO. I remember when I moved 
some of my own DX7 code to DX8 I had to remove almost 50% of the code 
because initialization has become much cleaner and easier and much 
functionality was completely cleaned up. Generally, the DX8 upgrade was 
long overdue and well done.

Regards,

